 this timely volume experts from both the academic and policy worlds present 13 different country case studies drawn from across the globe-including established and newer states, large and smaller states, those on the rise and those in apparent decline-to identify what these key players consider to be their national security priorities, how they go about providing national security, how they manage national security, and what role they see for their armed forces now and in the future. The book concludes that relative standing and the balance of power remains important to each state, and that all see an important role for armed forces in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aNational security. 0aWorld politicsy1989-. 4aContested Concepts. 4aNational Security. 4aalliances. 4aarmed forces. 4abalance of power. 4adefence. 4arising powers. 4athreat. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aDorman, Andrew M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaufman, Joyce P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479157140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791571.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles